				<p><p>In general, hard real-time OSes are used when there is a (usually periodic) task that is terminally critical, i.e. a process that needs to be run every few milliseconds, for example, and which, when queued, <strong>must</strong> be completed within a given time window to avoid a system failure. Note that "system failure" in this case doesn't have to mean that it will fry your CPU or break your robot, but instead that the resulting behaviour is considered a breach of the system's <strong>critical</strong> specifications, such as user safety or the like.</p>

<p>You may want to check out <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real-time_computing#Criteria_for_real-time_computing" rel="nofollow noreferrer">the criteria for different categories of real-time computing on Wikipedia</a></p>
</p><br>
